scTyper: a comprehensive pipeline for the cell typing analysis of single-cell RNA-seq data

1 Data preparation

scTyper uses two types of input data
      - raw scRNA-seq data of 10x genomics platform. ex)I1.fastq, R1.fastq, R2.fastq
      - pre-processed seurat object : a seurat object in which the processing steps of’QC’,‘Cell Ranger’ and’Seurat processing’ have been completed.

1.1 Load data

# load test scRNA-seq dataset
library(scTyper)
system(paste("tar -zxvf", system.file("extdata/test.seurat.rda.tar.gz", package = "scTyper")))
test.seurat=get(load(file.path(getwd(), "test.seurat.rda")))
  • We provide The test data consists of 407 cells and 14,985 genes.
  • This data is already organized and pre-processed (QC, Cell Ranger and Seurat processing have been already processed).
  • lt is available at GitHub (scTyper/inst/extdata/GSE103322.seurat.rda).

1.2 Phenotype data (Required)

# example phenotype data (csv format)
pheno.fn=system.file("extdata/pheno_info_test.csv", package = "scTyper")

Users need to make the sample phenotype information table as input for pipeline in a tabular form ‘.csv’ format. The order of the columns must follow the example template and the names of the columns be formatted as Sample_ID and TissueType.
      Sample_ID : Sample name of single cell RNA sequencing dataset.
      TissueType : Type of tissue that is composed of cells with similar structure and act together to perform a specific function.
              ex) Normal, Cancer etc.

  • Example
Sample_ID TissueType
sample_1 Cancer
sample_2 Cancer
sample_3 Normal
sample_4 Normal
sample_5 Normal

1.3 Marker selection

The scTyper package provides manually curated and pre-installed cell marker databases comprised of ‘scTyper.db’ and ‘CellMarker DB’ for cell typing. Users can choose and combine the set of markers from both database.
User can easily search the set of markers from both databases, which are uniquely labeled using unified nomenclature. For example, a cell marker label ‘Puram.2017.HNSCC.TME’ was designated by concatenating the first author name of the publication (‘Puram’), publication year (‘2017’), tissue type/cancer type (‘HNSCC’), and categories of cell composition (‘TME’, tumor microenvironment).

The input of marker parameter is elements of #Identifier, #StudyName, columns of both marker database or user-defined marker list. Following is examples:

  • #StudyName column of marker database
    One study has multiple cell types. If you want to use the set of marker in one or more study, user can choose and combine set of marker with #StudyName columns.
# StudyName
marker="Puram.2017.HNSCC.TME"
marker=c("Kawai.2018.Liver", "Li.2017.CRC.TME")
  • #Identifier column of marker database
    If user want to use individual cell types from studies, user can choose and combine paticular cell types with #Identifier columns.
# Identifier
marker=c("Costea.2013.OSCC.CAF:Normal cell:NF", "Costea.2013.OSCC.CAF:Cancer cell:CAF_D",
         "Elyada.2019.PDAC.CAF:Cancer cell:iCAF", "Elyada.2019.PDAC.CAF:Cancer cell:myCAF")
  • list of user-defined marker
    If you don’t have a set of markers of interest or want to define your own, you can enter a user-defined marker list.
# user defined marker list
marker=list(T_cell=c("CD2", "CD3D", "CD3E", "CD3G"),
            Fibroblast=c("FAP", "PDPN", "COL1A2", "DCN", "COL3A1", "COL6A1"),
            Macrophage=c("CD14", "CD163", "CD68", "FCGR2A", "CSF1R"),
            Dendritic_cell=c("CD40", "CD80", "CD83", "CCR7"),
            Mast_cell=c("CMA1", "MS4A2", "TPSAB1", "TPSB2"),
            Myocyte=c("ACTA1", "ACTN2", "MYL2", "MYH2"),
            Endothelial.cell=c("PECAM1", "VWF", "ENG"),
            B_Plasma_cell=c("SLAMF7", "CD79A", "BLNK", "FCRL5"),
            Epithelial_cell=c("KRT14", "KRT17", "KRT6A", "KRT5", "KRT19", "KRT8",
                              "KRT16", "KRT18", "KRT6B", "KRT15", "KRT6C", "KRTCAP3","EPCAM", "SFN"))
  • Note: If there is a duplicate gene in the selected marker, it is excluded in the cell typing process.
  • Note: If there is only one gene in the cell type of the marker, the user should use “Average” of the cell typing method.

1.3.1 Modification of the marker database (Optional)

If you want to modify marker database, you can change the ‘sigTyper.db.txt’ file in the ‘scTyper/extdata’ directory and then use the “update.sig.db()” function to modify the original marker database.

update.sig.db(sig.db.path = system.file(sig.db.path="extdata/sigTyper.DB.txt", package = "scTyper"), db.name=c("sigTyper.db"), output.dir=system.file("/data",package = "scTyper"))

2 Run scTyper()

scTyper is comprised of the modularized processes of ‘QC’, ‘Cell Ranger’, ‘Seurat processing’, ‘cell typing’, and ‘malignant cell typing’. Pre-processing step includes QC, Cell Ranger, Seurat processing. Cell typing algorithms are implemented to estimate the expression of cell marker sets, including NTP, ES(pre-ranked GSEA), and Average(average expression values). Also in malignant cell typing, inferred DNA copy numbers are estimated by an inferCNV R package. These processes can be customized by manipulating the parameters for each process. scTyper can be run as a single command like a following example.

  • Runing (pre-processing skip, NTP cell typing with inferCNV at cell level) 
celltyped.seurat=scTyper(seurat.object=test.seurat,
                         marker="Puram.2017.HNSCC.TME",
                         wd = getwd(),
                         output.name = "scTyper.output",
                         pheno.fn = pheno.fn,
                         qc = FALSE,
                         run.cellranger=FALSE,
                         norm.seurat=FALSE,
                         cell.typing.method="NTP",
                         level="cell",
                         run.inferCNV=TRUE,
                         proj.name = "scTyper",
                         gene.ref.gtf="/data/pubdata/ngs_ref/cellranger/refdata-cellranger-GRCh38-1.2.0/genes/genes.gtf",
                         feature.to.test = "tissue.type",
                         cells.test_excluded=c("Epithelial_cell", "Unresolved_cell"),
                         cells.test_reference = "Normal",
                         malignant.cell.type="Epithelial_cell",
                         report.mode=TRUE,
                         mc.cores = 1)

3.1 inferCNV parameter description in scTyper()

InferCNV is an analysis method for inferring copy number variations (CNVs) from single-cell RNA-seq data. Please refer to the parameters below for more detailed information when running inferCNV. These are parameters required for gene cluster detection in inferCNV.

feature.to.test : Cell group for permutation t.test in the inferCNV process. The value is “tissue.type” or “cell.type”, the column header name of the metadata in the Seurat object.
cells.test_excluded The value is a cell to be excluded in permutation T.test from the inferCNV process.
cells.test_reference The value containing the classification of the reference cell to be used by the cell to infer cnv in permutation T.test

4 scTyper() final output

  • final output of scTyper() is a Seurat object : scTyper() function returns a Seurat object, which is a popular data type for the subsequent analyses and biological interpretation of scRNA-seq. The seurat object includes the inferred cell type and cnv core as a result of cell typing. The Seurat object is a class allowing for the storage and manipulation of single-cell data. seurat object includes any piece of information associated with a cell (examples include read depth, alignment rate, experimental batch, or subpopulation identity) or feature (ENSG name, variance).

The following is a metadata column that stores pipeline results. - Analysis result column name of meta data in seurat object:
- cell.type: Inferred cell type result
- cnv.score: copy number variation score estimated by malignant cell typing (inferCNV)
- malignant.st: logical value of malignant cell estimated by malignant cell typing (inferCNV)

  • Report file : If report.mode=TRUE in scTyper() parameter, the results and the executed processes are automatically documented as a report. report.mode is a function used to combine the results into one unified file. The report summarizes the processing steps, cell typing and clustering results, and visualizing the results plots. This may help users reproduce their analysis workflows.

  • Automatically generated output directory : The result files are created automatically in output directory that users setted by parameter ‘wd’ and ‘output.name’ according to your processing step.

            - 00_qc : Directory of FastQC output
            - 01_count : Directory of CellRanger output
            - 02_NTP : Directory of NTP output
            - 03_inferCNV : Directory of inferCNV output
            - data : Directory of RData (rda). ‘seurat.rda’ (final output) saved.

5 Visualization

If “report.mode=TRUE” is set true in the scTyper(), the user will get a seurat object as an output.

  • Cell type statistics across samples 
cell.type.tbl=table(celltyped.seurat$cell.type)
ct.sample.tbl=table(celltyped.seurat$cell.type, celltyped.seurat$sample.name)

celltype.stat=cbind(cell.type.tbl, ct.sample.tbl)
colnames(celltype.stat)[1]="Total"
kable(celltype.stat) %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "striped", full_width = F, position = "left")

    A bar plot shows the distribution of cell types for the samples.

  • Proportion of cell types across samples
    A bar plot shows the proportion of cell type across sample.
ct.sample.proportion=apply(ct.sample.tbl, 2, function(a) a/sum(a))
barplot(ct.sample.proportion, las=2, ylab="Proportion (%)", cex.names=0.8, cex.axis=0.8, legend.text = rownames(ct.sample.proportion), args.legend = list(x = 'right', bty='n', inset=c(-0.3,0), xpd = TRUE, cex=0.7))

  • inferred cell types by cell typing method
    t-SNE plot with colors representing the inferred cell type label.
cols=rainbow_hcl(length(levels(celltyped.seurat$cell.type))); names(cols)=levels(celltyped.seurat$cell.type)
p1=DimPlot(celltyped.seurat, reduction = 'tsne',group.by="cell.type",label=F,cols=cols, pt.size=0.2); p1=LabelClusters(plot = p1, id = "cell.type", size = 3)

6 Example

  • Runing pre-processing skip and ES cell typing with inferCNV at cell level
    If user want to use “ES” cell typing method and run inferCNV at cell level, see the following parameters.
celltyped.seurat=scTyper(seurat.object=test.seurat,
                         marker="Puram.2017.HNSCC.TME",
                         wd = getwd(),
                         output.name = "scTyper.output",
                         pheno.fn = pheno.fn,
                         qc = FALSE,
                         run.cellranger=FALSE,
                         norm.seurat=FALSE,
                         cell.typing.method="ES",
                         level="cell",
                         run.inferCNV=TRUE,
                         proj.name = "scTyper",
                         gene.ref.gtf="/data/pubdata/ngs_ref/cellranger/refdata-cellranger-GRCh38-1.2.0/genes/genes.gtf",
                         feature.to.test = "tissue.type",
                         cells.test_excluded=c("Epithelial_cell", "Unresolved_cell"),
                         cells.test_reference = "Normal",
                         malignant.cell.type="Epithelial_cell",
                         report.mode=TRUE,
                         mc.cores = 1)
  • Runing pre-processing(QC, CellRanger, Normalization) and NTP cell typing with inferCNV at cell level
    If user want to run all pipelines with NTP cell typing method at cell level, see the following parameters.
###### Running all step (User's data)
processed.celltyped.seurat=scTyper(marker="Puram.2017.HNSCC.TME",
                                   wd="/data/Rpackage/scTyper",
                                   output.name = "test.result",
                                   pheno.fn="/data/Rpackage/scTyper/data/pheno_info_test.csv",
                                   qc = TRUE,
                                   run.cellranger=TRUE,
                                   norm.seurat=TRUE,
                                   cell.typing.method="NTP",
                                   level="cell",
                                   run.inferCNV=TRUE,
                                   proj.name = "scTyper",
                                   fastqc.path="/data/program/bin/fastqc",
                                   fastq.dir="/data/Rpackage/scTyper/test",
                                   fq1.idx="_R1_001.fastq",
                                   fq2.idx="_R2_001.fastq",
                                   cellranger.path="/data/program/bin/cellranger",
                                   cellranger.ref.dir="/data/pubdata/ngs_ref/cellranger/refdata-cellranger-GRCh38-1.2.0",
                                   gene.ref.gtf="/data/pubdata/ngs_ref/cellranger/refdata-cellranger-GRCh38-1.2.0/genes/genes.gtf",
                                   feature.to.test = "tissue.type",
                                   cells.test_excluded=c("Epithelial_cell", "Unresolved_cell"),
                                   cells.test_reference = "Normal",
                                   malignant.cell.type="Epithelial_cell",
                                   report.mode=TRUE,
                                   mc.cores = 1)
